  "prompt": "What is slyme?",
  "response": "\"Slyme\" typically refers to a South Korean R&B and hip-hop group that was active in the mid-2000s. Here are some key points about Slyme:\n\n### Overview of Slyme\n\n- **Formation and Debut:** Slyme debuted in 2004 under YG Entertainment, one of South Korea's leading entertainment companies.\n  \n- **Members:**\n  - **Sumpung (Yoon Il-sang):** Leader and main rapper.\n  - **Tag (Choi Seok-ho):** Rapper.\n  - **Swan:** Vocalist.\n  - **Luke (Kim Jin-pyo):** Vocalist.\n  - **Andy (Ahn Hyun-woo):** Vocalist, later pursued a successful solo career.\n  - **John (Hong Jong-hyun):** Vocalist.\n  - **Hangeng (Lee Han-geng):** The leader and main rapper, later joined the Chinese boy band Super Junior-M.\n\n- **Musical Style:** Slyme was known for their eclectic blend of R&B, hip-hop, and electronic music. They incorporated various genres and experimental sounds, setting them apart in the K-pop scene.\n\n- **Notable Works:**\n  - **\"One More Time\":** One of their popular tracks that showcased their unique style.\n  - **\"Rocket\":** Another hit song that gained significant attention.\n  \n- **Impact and Legacy:** Slyme was recognized for pushing the boundaries of K-pop with their innovative music and performances. They contributed to the diversification of the South Korean music industry during their active years.\n\n- **Disbandment:** Slyme officially disbanded in 2011. Post-disbandment, members pursued various solo careers in music, acting, and other entertainment fields. For instance, Hangeng became part of Super Junior-M, focusing on the Mandarin-speaking market, while Andy established himself as a solo artist.\n\n### Other Possible Meanings\n\nWhile the South Korean group is the most prominent reference, \"slyme\" could also be a misspelling or variation of the word \"slime,\" which refers to:\n\n- **Slime (Material):** A viscous, often colorful substance popular among children and used for sensory play.\n- **Slime in Popular Culture:** Often associated with gooey effects in movies, comics, and as a metaphor for something slippery or deceitful.\n\nIf you were referring to something else by \"slyme,\" please provide additional context, and I'd be happy to help!",
